   {:e #blake3 "ab2fdb0e85290ff1abf5f9e869b8b34f2f7c9a9a11c36e1813ee3247ecb08964" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-0ce58460; Session entity: :recon/trace-f18cd6943ee5c4c6; Session entity: :recon/trace-a340ca6f5d081997; Session entity: :task/t-04364857; Session entity: :task/t-349e769b; DEEP-REVIEW-2: Cross-cutting architectural insight — the Incremental/Batch Duality Invariant. SOUND-ISO tests one instance of a general pattern: MaterializedViews (incremental) vs compute_fitness (batch). But the same duality exists in: (1) LIVE view (incremental LWW per apply_datoms) vs full resolution (batch via ConflictSet from_datoms). (2) Secondary indexes (incremental per apply_datoms) vs from_datoms rebuild (batch). (3) Frontier (incremental per transact) vs Frontier::current computed from datoms (batch). Each pair can diverge independently. Testing them one at a time misses the pattern. The FORMAL FIX is a new invariant: INV-STORE-IDX-005 'Every incrementally-maintained data structure in the Store MUST have a batch-recompute function, and for any store state S, incremental(S) == batch(S).' This single invariant captures ALL incremental/batch divergences. The TEST is a proptest: build a store via random sequence of N transactions (including retractions), then verify: (a) store.views.fitness() == compute_fitness_batch(&store), (b) store.live_value(e,a) == resolve(store.datoms_for(e,a)), (c) store.entity_index == rebuild_entity_index(&store.datoms), (d) store.frontier == Frontier::from_datoms(&store.datoms). If ANY of these fail, we have found a divergence. This is strictly more powerful than SOUND-ISO alone.; DEEP-REVIEW-3: SOUND-LIVE should be upgraded from defensive (debug_assert) to corrective (fix the LIVE view). The current LIVE view update path (store.rs:1124) skips Retract datoms entirely. The actual fix is: when processing a Retract datom for (entity, attribute, value), check if live_view[(entity, attribute)] == (value, _). If so, REMOVE the entry from live_view (the value has been retracted with no replacement). The retract-then-assert case already works correctly because the assert in the same tx overwrites the LIVE entry with the new value. The ONLY broken case is bare retraction (retract without replacement). Fixing this requires: (1) In apply_datoms, after the insert-into-BTreeSet guard, add an else branch for Op::Retract that removes the LIVE entry if the retracted value matches. (2) In from_datoms, same logic. (3) Also formalize the retraction protocol as INV-COHERENCE-002: 'Under Cardinality::One, every Retract datom for (entity, attribute, value) where the LIVE view shows (value, _) MUST be accompanied by either (a) an Assert datom for the same (entity, attribute) with a different value in the same transaction, OR (b) the transaction MUST include :tx/bare-retraction = true to explicitly mark intentional deletion. Bare retractions without the flag are a protocol violation.' This makes bare retractions explicit rather than accidental. The flag distinguishes intentional deletion (marking something as no longer true) from protocol violation (forgot to assert a replacement).; Session entity: :task/t-1d83231f; Session entity: :task/t-2dc2e39d; Session entity: :recon/trace-92a60031440995e3; DEEP-REVIEW-4: SOUND-NAN should use FiniteF64 newtype instead of scattered is_finite() checks. The formal-methods approach to NaN propagation is to make NaN UNREPRESENTABLE in the type system, not to check for it at runtime. Approach: (1) Create FiniteF64 newtype in a new file crates/braid-kernel/src/finite.rs. Construction: FiniteF64::new(f: f64) -> Option<FiniteF64> that returns None if f.is_nan() || f.is_infinite(). The inner value is private. (2) Implement arithmetic traits (Add, Sub, Mul, Div) that check results. Division by FiniteF64(0.0) returns None (not NaN). (3) Implement Ord (total ordering — safe because NaN is excluded). This is the key advantage: FiniteF64 can be sorted, compared, and used in BTreeMap keys. f64 cannot. (4) Use FiniteF64 as the return type for all spectral metrics: eigenvalues, Fiedler value, Cheeger constant, spectral gap, Renyi entropy, Ricci curvature. (5) Functions that can fail (division by zero) return Option<FiniteF64>. (6) The caller decides what to do with None — typically fallback to a sensible default. This is the ordered_float crate pattern but without the external dependency and with stricter guarantees. The result: NaN propagation becomes a compile-time error (type mismatch when passing FiniteF64 where f64 is expected), not a runtime check.; Session entity: :task/t-21977f18; DEEP-REVIEW-1: Root cause of 4 failing guidance tests identified. The C8-FIX-5 code path in telemetry_from_store() (methodology.rs:404-425) checks for :spec/element-type datoms to distinguish 'braid-like projects' from 'external projects'. The 4 failing tests create :spec/inv-test-XXX entities with :db/ident but do NOT create :spec/element-type datoms. So store_has_spec_datoms = false, triggering the external-project fallback which gives spec_language credit only when :exploration/body or :task/title datoms exist. The tests only have :db/doc datoms, so total_spec = 0 instead of the expected 5 or 3. The fix has two parts: (1) Update the tests to include :spec/element-type datoms for entities that represent spec elements — this makes the tests accurately model a spec-using project. (2) Consider whether the C8-FIX-5 detection should ALSO check for :db/ident starting with ':spec/' as a secondary indicator of a spec-aware project, since that's the pattern actually used by spec entities. This is important: the test failures are NOT a regression in M(t) logic — they are a test/code divergence caused by the C8-FIX-5 enhancement that properly handles external projects but left the tests behind.; Session entity: :task/t-6ab50e4a; Session entity: :task/t-d53d9f98; Session entity: :recon/trace-d97b5c06beccc99d; Session entity: :recon/trace-6967bcc443c9a1e1\nSession entity: :task/t-49d114e3" :op :assert}
